      <hedline>
        <hl1>White House Advocate</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Lou Glasse letter comments on August 12 article on Republican Repr Rick Lazio's questioning of accomplishments of Hillary Rodham Clinton, Democratic rival for US Senate seat from New York</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lazio Disputes Mrs. Clinton on Quiet Accomplishments'' (news article, Aug. 12): Hillary Rodham Clinton's dedication and effective advocacy are well known by most people working on legislation to help women and children.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lazio Disputes Mrs. Clinton on Quiet Accomplishments'' (news article, Aug. 12): Hillary Rodham Clinton's dedication and effective advocacy are well known by most people working on legislation to help women and children.</p>
        <p>A few years ago, Mrs. Clinton's staff invited me to meet with about 15 older women in New York City. We discussed their fear of breast cancer, and why more women did not get mammograms. No members of the media were present.</p>
        <p>This was the first of a number of such meetings that Mrs. Clinton held across the country. Afterward, she reported her findings at a White House event at which a number of us spoke about the need for a yearly mammogram for older women.</p>
        <p>Now, Medicare rules permit yearly mammograms. I am confident that Mrs. Clinton's persuasiveness was essential in bringing about this change.</p>
        <p>LOU GLASSE  Poughkeepise, N.Y., Aug. 14, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a former director, New York State Office for the Aging.</p>
      </block>
